  "prompt": "How many numbers between 200 and 300 are such which are divisible by 13?",
  "response": "To determine how many numbers between 200 and 300 are divisible by 13, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Find the smallest number \u2265 200 divisible by 13:**\n\n   Divide 200 by 13:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{200}{13} \\approx 15.3846\n   \\]\n   \n   Since we need the smallest integer greater than or equal to 15.3846, we take **16**.\n   \n   Multiply by 13:\n   \\[\n   16 \\times 13 = 208\n   \\]\n   \n   So, **208** is the smallest number \u2265 200 divisible by 13.\n\n2. **Find the largest number \u2264 300 divisible by 13:**\n\n   Divide 300 by 13:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{300}{13} \\approx 23.0769\n   \\]\n   \n   Since we need the largest integer less than or equal to 23.0769, we take **23**.\n   \n   Multiply by 13:\n   \\[\n   23 \\times 13 = 299\n   \\]\n   \n   So, **299** is the largest number \u2264 300 divisible by 13.\n\n3. **Determine the number of terms in this arithmetic sequence:**\n\n   The sequence of numbers divisible by 13 between 200 and 300 is:\n   \\[\n   208, 221, 234, \\ldots, 299\n   \\]\n   \n   This is an arithmetic sequence with:\n   - First term (\\(a_1\\)) = 208\n   - Common difference (\\(d\\)) = 13\n   - Last term (\\(a_n\\)) = 299\n   \n   The formula to find the number of terms (\\(n\\)) in an arithmetic sequence is:\n   \\[\n   a_n = a_1 + (n - 1) \\times d\n   \\]\n   \n   Plugging in the known values:\n   \\[\n   299 = 208 + (n - 1) \\times 13\n   \\]\n   \n   Subtract 208 from both sides:\n   \\[\n   91 = (n - 1) \\times 13\n   \\]\n   \n   Divide both sides by 13:\n   \\[\n   n - 1 = 7\n   \\]\n   \n   Add 1 to both sides:\n   \\[\n   n = 8\n   \\]\n\n**Final Answer:**\n\\[\n\\boxed{8}\n\\]",
  "temperature": 1.0,
